The problem with the first one is that what you are declaring is effectively a const pointer named 'a' to 10 consecutive memory locations allocated for the size of int.  The second is a declaration of a variable-length array named a.<p>So, for example, you can't do this:<p><p><p><p><p><pre><code>       int a[10];
       int b[10];

       a=b;
</code></pre>
You get a type error, or an lvalue error, because you can't assign anything to a constant.
